1. Meyer's Singleton (the simplest):

```cpp
class Singleton {
public:
    static Singleton& instance() {
        static Singleton inst; // thread-safe initialization guaranteed by C++11
        return inst;
    }

private:
    Singleton() = default;
    ~Singleton() = default;
    Singleton(const Singleton&) = delete;
    Singleton& operator=(const Singleton&) = delete;
};
```

Explain that static local variable's initialization is done only once, even in multithreaded context, due to "magic statics". The standard ensures thread-safe initialization.

2. Using std::call_once:

